related.title: Another victory for the little guy
related.headline: Another victory for the little guy

article.headline: Nets travel to Minnesota on Wednesday
article.linkText: Nets extend win streak to 14, Frank now 13-0
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Lawrence Frank and the New Jersey Nets had to work a lot harder than expected against undermanned Toronto for their NBA-best 14th straight win. A bigger challenge will come Wednesday when Frank and the Nets travel to Minnesota to play the Midwest Division-leading Timberwolves. "They're the best team in the league right now, period," Nets forward Richard Jefferson said. "Have we had success against them the past three years? Yeah." The Nets set up the big matchup by getting 25 points and 15 rebounds from Kenyon Martin in holding off the Raptors 86-74 on Tuesday night. "Everybody's talking like it's Game 7," Jason Kidd said of the game against the Timberwolves, who are 21-7 at home and coming off a 108-102 win at Milwaukee on Tuesday. "We're getting ahead of ourselves," Kidd added. "It's not the playoffs. Minnesota played tonight, we played tonight. Everybody seems to want to make this into a bigger game." It easily is the toughest test since Frank replaced Byron Scott on Jan. 26 as coach of the two-time defending Eastern Conference champions. Only four of the Nets' wins in their franchise-record streak have come against teams with winning records. "I haven't even thought about Minnesota," said Frank, whose 13-0 coaching start is a record for major professional sports in North America. "We will not use any crutches. This game is on the schedule and we are prepared to win." Handing the Raptors their season-high sixth straight loss should not have been much of a challenge. Toronto played without starters Jalen Rose, Vince Carter and Alvin Williams. However, Toronto got the 33-year-old Frank a little miffed in the second half, cutting a 19-point lead late in the third quarter to 73-68 with 8:34 to go. Frank called two timeouts during the 14-0 run and picked up a technical foul for seemingly mocking the officials for making a call for the Nets. "They made shots. They got to the basket and they made free throws," Martin said. "They made it a game. They didn't quit playing. We had to buckle back down and get some stops." Martin hit a set shot to ignite a 10-3 spurt that secured the win and put Frank in the record book for best start by a new coach or manager. Joe Morgan of the Boston Red Sox won 12 straight in 1988 after taking over for John McNamara, and Jim Price won that many with the National League team in New York in 1884. The team was known as both the Gothams and the Giants that season, according to the Elias Sports Bureau. Kidd added 17 points and seven assists. Kerry Kittles had 15 points, and Rodney Rogers scored all 12 of his in the second quarter as the Nets opened a 15-point halftime lead. Roger Mason Jr. led the Raptors with a career-high 18 points in his first NBA start. Milt Palacio and Donyell Marshall added 13 points apiece for Toronto, which shot 39.1 percent from the field. "We wanted to keep fighting," Toronto rookie Chris Bosh said. "We're not going to lay down and die. We will keep fighting. The whole team kept going." The Raptors got more bad news less than an hour before the game when a sore knee sidelined Williams, their point guard. The Raptors showed the effects early, shooting 2-of-18 from the field and turning the ball over nine times in one stretch of more than 15 minutes, including six straight turnovers.

Game notes
Frank will ring the bell to open the New York Stock Exchange on Thursday. ... Nets backup G Hubert Davis has not lost in 27 games. He was released by the Pistons after they won 13 straight, and he has won 14 in a row with New Jersey. ... The Nets had a 45-30 rebounding edge. ... Toronto signed G Jannero Pargo for the rest of the season. He had two points in 17 minutes. ... San Antonio also had a 13-game winning streak earlier this season.
